<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-181-293 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 566 532</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 8 1991 v25 n14 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bank takes its philosophy to heart; PCs join integrity, serviceand teamwork in contributing to bottom line. (On Site, MichiganNational Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Fitzgerald, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Charles Kight, executive vice president of consumer banking andinformation technology at Michigan National Corp, says thephilosophy of his information system department is to prioritizespeedy and accurate customer service.andP;  Michigan National Corp isone of the largest banks in the state, with 188 branches and $11billion in net worth.andP;  The focus of Kight's department is onreducing the time it takes for a teller or customer service personto handle a customer's query.andP;  Towards this end, the bank isinstalling IBM PS/2 55SXs in its administrative offices and at allits branches.andP;  The microcomputers allow employees easy access tothe company's main data base, and by using IBM's Callpathingsoftware, customer information can be transferred from oneterminal to another as the telephone call is being transferred.andO;The bank also uses microcomputers and multimedia software tocreate full motion videos for training and promotion.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Michigan National Corp. (Communication systems).andO;Ticker:    MNCO.andO;Topic:     MISCase StudyBankingInformation resources managementMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>